{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:10:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:10:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2366"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79758"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65063"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"833"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27323"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79758"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of pain in the back of her right ankle. The pain occurred while jumping during a volleyball game. She heard a \u0027pop\u0027 sound and was unable to continue playing. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in mild discomfort. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has an antalgic gait. There is no skin breach or obvious deformity. With her knees in prone position, the right ankle rests in a dorsiflexed position compared to the left. There is tenderness over the posterior ankle. Plantar flexion is weak and painful. There is no plantar flexion when the calf is squeezed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Achilles tendon rupture","Calcaneal fracture","Medial subtalar dislocation","Achilles tendonitis","Anterior talofibular ligament tear"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tendon rupture\u003C/strong\u003E. The mechanism of sudden forced plantar flexion during jumping, accompanied by a \u0027pop\u0027 sound, is typical. Key examination findings include weakness in plantar flexion, increased ankle dorsiflexion at rest, and a positive Thompson test (absence of plantar flexion when squeezing the calf muscle).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcaneal fracture\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from high-energy axial loading (e.g., fall from height) rather than sports injuries. Patients usually cannot bear weight and have significant swelling and bruising.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial subtalar dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with forceful inversion injuries and presents with obvious foot deformity, with the foot locked in supination and medial displacement of the calcaneus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tendonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an overuse injury causing gradual onset of pain and swelling. It does not present with sudden loss of function or a positive Thompson test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior talofibular ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with inversion injuries to a plantar-flexed foot. Pain is typically anterolateral rather than posterior, and the anterior drawer test would be positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Achilles tendon is formed by the confluence of the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles. Complete rupture requires urgent orthopaedic referral as early surgical repair (within 48 hours) generally leads to better outcomes than delayed treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden onset of pain behind the ankle during forceful plantar flexion is characteristic of Achilles tendon rupture","Thompson test (lack of plantar flexion on calf squeeze) is diagnostic of Achilles tendon rupture","A positive Thompson test, weakness in plantar flexion, and increased ankle dorsiflexion are the key clinical findings in Achilles tendon rupture"],"references":["Leppilahti J, Orava S. Total Achilles tendon rupture. A review. Sports Med 1998; 25:79. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9519398/","van der Vlist AC, Breda SJ, Oei EHG, et al. Clinical risk factors for Achilles tendinopathy: a systematic review. Br J Sports Med 2019; 53:1352. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30718234/","Aldridge T. Diagnosing heel pain in adults. Am Fam Physician 2004; 70:332. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2004/0715/p332.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65063"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65063"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T14:38:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T14:38:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions"